                    <item>
              <title>Computer-marked assessment (ICT skills)</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/265</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/265</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Some qualifications demand evidence of basic ICT skills, but marking and giving feedback on the entire range required is intensive of tutor time.
<p>
This social work course – part of a degree where the professional body requires the equivalent of the European Computer Driving Licence – includes staged ICT study sessions, in each of which students first read instructional materials and complete activities, and then take a 15 question computer-marked assessment (CMA). They can attempt each question three times, with reducing marks and increasing hints.
<p>
The CMAs, ICT-specific TMAs, and an ICT task in the end-of-course assessment are compulsory, so that the professional requirements are fulfilled.

[Mick McCormick, Ingrid Nix]
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 28 Jul 2008 13:09:04 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Digital threads</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/162</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/162</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Reduce pressure on unconfident learners by teaching a balance of traditional and new skills, with material that is culturally acceptable and relevant. </strong></p>
<p>In this <a href="http://www.wea.org.uk/">WEA</a> course, British Asian women are trained in the use of computerised sewing machines. Some of the students have language and literacy difficulties, and one challenge is to overcome their fear in using computers. The computer component of the course is carefully balanced &ndash; eg 2 hours embroidery to 1 hour computing. Some internet activities, such as searching for patterns, are largely self-directed; use of the sewing machines is more strongly tutor-directed, with peer mentoring. Learners are not pressured to complete a portfolio. For some learners, a Women&rsquo;s Centre venue and creche facilities are necessary for them to be able to take part. Designs from the internet provide a more culturally relevant supplement to the designs of Disney characters which come packaged with the machines. [John Cook, Ian Harford]</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 29 Apr 2008 10:58:08 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Basic skills training in a football club</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/92</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/92</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[Newcastle United Football Club’s premises includes a purpose-built learning centre, servicing over 1000 learners a week, attracted by the powerful draw of the football club.

In an informal, relaxed and inclusive atmosphere, learners select activities from an extensive range of programmes in literacy, numeracy and ICT, setting their own learning goals with the guidance of centre staff.

Self-directed online study, including interactive tutorials and simulations, helps everyone progress at their own pace.

[Phil McBride]]]></description>
